{
  "text": " Dahu tambu la nonse. Mulivuti. My name is Yvonne Makesakala. That is Tonga that I'm speaking to you. In Tonga, I was actually saying, you're welcome. And I'm also greeting you. How are you doing? I live in Lusaka, Zambia. And that language is spoken here in Zambia. Not only is it spoken in Zambia, we have Tonga in Malawi, also in Zibabwe. And even in Mozambique, I'm a teacher by profession. I have been teaching from 1995 to be specific I've been teaching learning to read. And then I did my BA in Secondary Education. At a Wunto Talks, I will be teaching Tonga. Maybe you're asking yourself, why would I want to learn Tonga? Well, you know what? The world has actually become a very close unit. People can travel all over the world and learn each other's languages. So, I would like to encourage you to sign up with Wunto Talks so that you can learn how to speak Tonga and many other African languages. When you travel to Africa, from wherever you are in the world, at least you be able to learn how to greet and how to interact with the locals in that particular country. Now, when you sign up with Wunto Talks and you want to learn the language Tonga because you are coming to Zambia to visit or to do any other business, guess what? I am going to be your tutor. And I guarantee you that you will learn how to speak, to read and to write the language. Not only will you learn how to do all that, you are going to be able to stick to the locals. I will show you easy ways of which you will be able to communicate to anybody in the area where Tonga is spoken. We are Gui, Guambao, Zitonga. Zitonga, Chihuat Maningi. See you soon. Bye-bye. Moussiali, Cabo, Tu, Thiago, Buonana, Guu Wunto Talk.",
